{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17645967","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17645967"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:23:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:23:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18146"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18146","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18146"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10860"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82573"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10860","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10860"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18146"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67738"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7230"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25266"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25271"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82573","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82573"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ulnar nerve follows a specific path as it travels through the forearm.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following muscles does the ulnar nerve pass between in the forearm?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pronator teres","Flexor carpi radialis","Flexor carpi ulnaris","Palmaris longus","Pronator quadratus"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAfter passing posterior to the medial epicondyle of the humerus, the ulnar nerve enters the forearm by coursing between the humeral and ulnar heads of the \u003Cstrong\u003Eflexor carpi ulnaris\u003C/strong\u003E. This anatomical relationship is clinically relevant as it represents a potential site of nerve compression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other muscles mentioned have different anatomical relationships:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epronator teres\u003C/strong\u003E has two heads but is located more proximally in the forearm and relates to the median nerve rather than the ulnar nerve\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eflexor carpi radialis\u003C/strong\u003E lies on the radial side of the anterior forearm and has no direct relationship with the ulnar nerve\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epalmaris longus\u003C/strong\u003E is a superficial muscle in the anterior compartment that does not interact with the ulnar nerve\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epronator quadratus\u003C/strong\u003E is found in the deep anterior compartment near the wrist and is not associated with the course of the ulnar nerve\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The ulnar nerve courses through the forearm by passing between the humeral and ulnar heads of flexor carpi ulnaris.","The anatomical pathway of the ulnar nerve through the forearm is clinically significant for identifying potential compression sites."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Miniato MA, Anand P, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder. 2023 Jul 24. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725618","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Raszewski JA, Black AC, Launico MV, et al. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Hand Compartments. [Updated 2023 Oct 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/books/NBK532942/","McCausland C, Sawyer E, Eovaldi BJ, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder Muscles. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30521257","Paulsen, F., \u0026 Waschke, J. (Eds.). (2023). Sobotta Atlas of Anatomy, Vol. 1, English/Latin: General Anatomy and Musculoskeletal System (Vol. 1). Elsevier Health Sciences250"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67738"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18146"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67738","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67738"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-29T23:38:57+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-29T23:40:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10860"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82573"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identif